1. pybind11 (best modern way 👍)

This is the most popular and clean approach.

What you do:
Write a small C++ “binding” file
Include your header
Expose functions/classes to Python
Compile into a Python module (.so / .pyd)
Example
C++ header (mylib.hpp)
#pragma once

int add(int a, int b);
C++ implementation (mylib.cpp)
#include "mylib.hpp"

int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
Python binding (bindings.cpp)
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include "mylib.hpp"

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_MODULE(mylib, m) {
    m.def("add", &add);
}
Build (CMake example)
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.10)
project(mylib)

add_subdirectory(pybind11)

pybind11_add_module(mylib bindings.cpp mylib.cpp)

Then:

mkdir build
cd build
cmake ..
make

Now in Python:

import mylib
print(mylib.add(2, 3))